segments.text: Today is November the 2nd, and I am interviewing Dr. Linda Parrish, who was a former student in the College of Education, is now teaching in the Department of Industrial and Vocational.
Well, you probably want to get that down.
Okay, give me more.
I have a split appointment.
All right.
I'm 67% an educational psychologist.
Oh, okay.
And 33%.
in industrial, vocational, and technical education.
Okay.
Very good.
And if you've already looked at the questions, they don't have to be in any particular order.
I guess change is the one thing that I'm asking everybody about because you would have perceived it from a different, you know, deal when you were a student.
And then now as you teach and you see a lot of the changes, I guess that will give me a different type of
Well, most of the things I was focusing on is just as a professor, because this is my ninth year here.

I remember when I was hired as a professor that one of the things one of my professors said to me was, now, Linda, the hardest thing you're going to have to get used to is to act like a professor instead of a graduate student here.
And I said to him,
That's not any trouble at all.
I've always acted like a professor, even as a student here.
And he laughed and he says, you know, as a matter of fact, I think you have.
Did you start under Dean Hubert?
Yes.
Hubert hired me.
Sure, sure.
Okay, good.
Well, go ahead and tell me something about the ways that you have seen the changes and what you have perceived as being, what has impacted, what kind of things impacted change since you left?
Well, number one and two go together.
It felt like when I was looking at number one, the changes that I would tell you about are just so intricately woven with the people who have made the change, so I'll have to answer those together.
A major change in the College of Education has been the arrival of Dean Corrigan.

is a nationally visible figure and I can remember having a trip to El Paso planned the day that he was coming to interview and I called and rescheduled my trip because it was so important for me to meet Dean Corrigan and there were three wonderful candidates that all came in that I was teaching as off-campus
course in El Paso, and I didn't reschedule for anyone else, just for Karga, because I felt like whether he got this job or not, or whether he decided to come and offer it or not,
He was someone I really wanted to know and really wanted to meet because I had read so much of the things he was doing, particularly as they related to my field in educating disabled students.
So it was important for me to meet him.
I never was sorry that I rescheduled to do that because it was exciting and he's a very exciting person.
But I remember thinking to myself after he left from the interview, I wasn't sure what our chances were that we would get him here, but even though I've loved
being at Texas A&M, I thought, my goodness, if we get Dean Kargan, he's better than we deserve.
He's just so outstanding that we're going to really have to work hard.
That's what I thought.
I still, after working for him, think that he is just absolutely a wonderful dean.
He gives us national leadership.
But my perception is that
the faculty here are wonderful also.
And so maybe I'd feel like he's just as lucky as we are now.
My attitude is that.
I can't imagine why you would feel that you was better than you deserve.
Why in the world would you feel that?
I don't know.
I remember thinking that.
Perhaps because the climate was so different.
Now, you may not get this from a lot of people, but to me, the climate was extremely different.
Okay.
Though Dean Hubert had a lot of
good qualities.
His leadership style was so extremely different.
It was what you would expect at Texas A&M.
It was autocratic.
It was authoritarian.
It was all of those things.
And as a result, although we had some very good people here, I believe that they weren't reaching their potential because they were doing what they were told to do.
With a person like Corrigan coming, everyone
could do just about anything we had the courage to dream, and he would support it.

It got to be a joke where people were saying, try to avoid Corrigan in the elevator, because if you start up a conversation, he'll say, well, I expect you to do that, or, you know, go right ahead with it.
Whereas before, there had been, in my estimation, more of, well, let's go through 14 committees before we decide if that's an appropriate research.
Mm-hmm, mm-hmm.
And so, to me, that was a dramatic difference.
And as a result, some people felt more comfortable with Hubert.
Some felt more comfortable with Corrigan.
And not everybody's alike.
But at least those who are the thinkers and the doers and the self-initiators are really...
So that's more the change?
That's to me the major change since I've been here.
I think other things that have changed that have affected us is more faculty governance.
Faculty have
had very little in the history of our university to do and say with how things were going.
We teach and we serve and we work with students and we conduct research, which of course are all vital things of our profession.
But as far as the administration and governance, we haven't had all that much say until lately.
You were talking about governance and being a part of decision.
Right.
I think the faculty in the last four years has gotten a lot more vocal and been heard.
And that's not only because of the College of Education's stance in leadership, but also because the university's change in leadership.
We had, at the same time, a chancellor and a president come to this university to be a part of the faculty and replace the decision-making.
That is also when we were able to establish the Faculty Senate.
It's helped a lot.
I think it's given a lot of courage.
Now, there's also camps, of course, those who choose to be involved and those who rather the administration do it and say, you're paid to make the decisions, you do it, and leave me alone.
That's right.
I prefer to have some say so in what goes on administratively.
OK, good.
That wouldn't have happened in 1978 when I was the first assistant.
Now, tell me how you feel, the next question, about the college achieving its mission.
And was there a change since you were there in that interim period?
Was there more or less focus or emphasis on the teaching or the research or the service?
Everyone, I think, will tell you at a major university that we are told you must do an outstanding job at teaching.
That is a focus.
And you have to serve in committees, et cetera.
And you have to do research.
You have to do all three of these.
The truth of the matter is, when we put up the tenure and promotion,
Our research is looked at very heavily, and I'm in the Department of Educational Psychology, and we have some very strong researchers.
And to be in comparison with that group, you have to be conducting research, and you cannot be doing research that is deemed inappropriate or less...
Who decides whether your research is?
Is it your department head that decides what research to do?
No, I decide what research I will do.
Whether it's appropriate or acceptable.
Right.
The people ahead of me, I'm an associate professor.
My full professor colleagues in my department are currently, as we speak, even this year, looking at my credentials.
for promotion to full professor.
And so, well, it may be, it may not be.
This one's a real important one to me because this is what everybody wants to become is a full professor.
But the one, I guess, the most crucial is going from assistant to associate because that's where your tenure comes at that point, too.
So, and having already achieved that, I can tell you that had I not done a significant amount of research and outside funded research, which I do a great deal of,
I don't think I would have looked on as favorably.
And that's my perception.
It may not be true, but it is my perception of how we are judged.
I personally feel that the most important thing I do is teach.
And it irritates me.
to think that some top-notch researchers can be lousy teachers and remain at Texas A&M.
I believe it's easier to be a bad teacher and a good researcher and stay here than it would be to be a wonderful teacher and a mediocre researcher.
That's my perception.
That's interesting.
And because of the time constraints and because you're doing so many things, all of you as professors, do you feel a certain amount of pressure when you
when you don't have some ongoing research at all times?
I've never not had a funded research project.
Never.
I've got six.
I've got a half a million dollars this year in funded research.
Almost half a million dollars.
And I have never had...
A year that I've been a professor that I have not had outside funding research.
But you're also always teaching and you're also always doing that?
This is the first year in nine years that I am not teaching.
I have always taught and conducted research.
But because of the magnitude of the research grants I got this year, and I have 20 people hired doing research for me this year, I am only doing administration and other work.
Oh, absolutely.
And so I'm guest speaking all the time.
I go to people, do you need somebody to go into your classes with?
I know you did that in our classes somewhere very well.
Well, I have to do that because that's where you get the gratification is from your students.
And I suppose I'm just not cut out to be an administrator.
I like to touch people more often.
Okay.
Well, that's probably part of the next question then.
How has this tremendous growth
affected your work with students?
It's been awful.
I cannot tell you.
From 1978 to 1986, the largest class I had at A&M was 36 students.
Last semester, in the spring of 86, I had a class of 183.
Gosh.
That's one class.
That's right.
One class.
Special Education 110, Introduction to Special Education.
Let me tell you, I'll do anything to keep on teaching that class again.
I didn't know the students.
People will come up to me on campus now and say, oh, Dr. Parrish, I had you last spring.
There's no way you know them.
And I have had, I mean, I know my students, and I know where they're from, and I don't want to do that every year.
But somebody's doing it this semester.
With that many students?
Oh, yeah.
No, 240 in that class this semester.
It's worse because we had such a big increase.
Mercy.
That is.
So definitely it has affected the ability to work with students more on an individual basis.
In those kind of classes.
In the counseling type.
Okay.
In the overall survey classes.
This is a 110.
It's a freshman, sophomore level class.
And I hate that.
Of course, that's going on in chemistry, you know, everywhere.
But for the first five years I was here, I only taught graduate classes, and I think my biggest one of those was 18th.
I love that.
But undergraduates, I think that we need to keep our undergraduate classes small.
Those kids really need to know professors.
That's where you're setting foundations.
That's right.
Okay.
That leads me then to a little bit about how departments and colleges and so forth collaborate maybe with each other to alleviate maybe some of these problems or to enhance or to whatever.
What do you see?
there in the collaborative efforts?
I think we're doing better than we've done in the past, although we're still not as good as we should be.
My personal opinion is, if I had some vision for the future, is that we don't have departments at all.
We'd have a college of education, and we would have faculty who were interdisciplinary in nature,

But you would have someone, for example, in educational administration who could teach without going into its site what an administrator needs to know for disabled students in their mainstream schools.
And I just think that we would have a more effective program if we didn't realize department heads necessarily have to fight for resources for their departments.
And we have a lot of that.
All these people get along with each other, and they meet with policy committee meetings once a month, I think, within Corrigan, and I think they get along.
But then they, that's what they have to do.
I mean, that's the nature of their job.
So there's some of this turf protection, too.
You want to have, you know, your area protected, or is that... Oh, absolutely, absolutely.
And...
I don't know.

Maybe I'm also too idealistic to really be an effective administrator, but it seems to me that if we're all doing something very well, then we could eliminate any excess that we might have, and I don't know that we did, and work together in our students would really benefit.
I don't believe that we need to be governed by our present order.
Do you think that would ever happen?
Dean Corrigan did it at a university before he came here.
He had centers of inquiry, as I understand it.
I may be misrepresenting him, but I had read about what he did, and I was looking for that kind of thing to happen at A&M in the first three years he'd given up.
Did he try?
I mean, I know he set up some inquiry groups.
He set up inquiry groups, and I thought, aha, this is the first step, because he sent out wanting to know all of our interests.
And then we got together in centers of inquiry, inquiry groups, and those have been fun, but they haven't led to the demise of departments.
Well, and there was also, I understand, some resistance on some departments' part of not even to the point I have heard of
punishing the faculty members who got too involved in the inquiry groups.
Whereas in other departments, everybody was on all of them, or there was somebody on all sides.
That's right.
And I got to be involved from the very beginning, because I thought it was exciting and new.
Well, we got to meet different faculty.
Believe this or not, there were faculty in the College of Education in different departments that really don't know each other very well.
I have heard that also from several teachers, that because it has grown so fast, now people don't know each other or have the camaraderie that they enjoyed when it was just a very small group.
But we could.
There are ways to do it, even in big conglomerations.
Very good.
And do you see that all of these things have changed how other people see us as a college of education on a state level or even beyond?
You know, through your exposure.
That's very interesting.
I should go back to number five to say, we talked about inside the college.

Outside the college, just recently, we're beginning to work with the College of Science and the College of Liberal Arts to work on degree plans that reflect what the state is looking at, less teacher-ed kind of courses, those kind of things.
Those things should always be there, because whether we like it or not, in any major university, the College of Education is looked on as the ugly stepsister.
I have been told to my face that you were the weak link in this very strong chain, meaning the entire College of Education.
At A&M, you mean?
Oh, yes.
You have been told?
Yes, at A&M was where I was told by a department head in the College of Liberal Arts.
It is amazing to me if people don't understand it or if they just reject hearing it, if they don't know that, because that's the perception of the College of Education.
Maybe not so much here as all over the country, but it certainly is.
It's just a national phenomenon.
Now, with Dean Corrigan's coming and with his high visibility and his articulate nature and all of those types of things, we have been able to turn the corner at A&M.
I believe most of our higher ed administrators believe we're the best college.
I believe that.
I think they'll shakily believe that.
But I don't know if our colleagues in liberal arts and science and those people believe that.
You still have that respect for that, right?
That's interesting.
You have to understand, I'm married to the Associate Dean of Liberal Arts, so I party a lot with people in the foreign languages and literature.
And there's this air, maybe, of...
There is.
There definitely is that superiority here, but it's really hysterical because we tend to be flourishing, and the College of Education gets resources, and somebody flourishes.
Well, and isn't this college and the College of Liberal Arts the two fastest growing?
I believe that's what we heard at the last development council.
And business.
And business, okay.
So that's an interesting thing.
And, of course, well, to skip around a little bit,
What do you think then now with all these perspective changes and these things in the legislature and all the interpretation of these new bills, how do you think that's going to affect?
It's going to help us.
Okay.
Now a lot of people will say, oh my gosh, look, it's changing what we've done in the last 195 years.
To me, it's wonderful.
It's going to raise the esteem of teachers.
going to raise their position in the schools.
They're going to, in my estimation, be rewarded financially if they come out believing they are better.
Now, whether they're better or not, I'm not saying.
But the perception of them being better by not graduating, say, with 90 hours of education, which they don't, but everybody believes they do.
That's true.
then they're going to come out.
It's all perception.
But that's okay.
If it is perception, it is a good thing for them.
The thing of it is, the kids that come here to A&M are good students.
And people will say to me, ah, you know, A&M, you must have a wonderful college education.
Your students don't fail the exit test.
Okay, you've got 98% passing the exit test.
My answer to them is yes, I think we are good at A&M.
But I'm telling you that the kids who come to A&M could probably pass the exit test the day they arrive.
We get the cream of the crop to come to A&M.
So I can't take all the responsibility and the credit for making these wonderful teachers.
They're wonderful students when they come to us.
Okay, that's something that I keep hearing now from people about because we have had to raise the standards and because of the enrollment cap and because all of these other things that are happening.
I'm hearing, you know, are you leaving out, you know, your average students?
And are the people that are coming that are so fantastic, that are merit scholars, that are, you know, the cream of the crop, how many of those want to go into teaching?
Very few.
very few, but you can't blame them.
If I were going back to school today with the opportunities different than they were 25 years ago, I probably wouldn't major in education, but we've got to make education as
as competitive.
So what's going to do it?
Well, what's going to do it is raising our self-esteem.
And if that means getting a degree in liberal arts with a teaching certificate, I don't really care how we do it.
Just so we make these students competent professionals who believe in themselves.
And so I think all of these things, I'm willing to try them because we're not succeeding for our teachers now.
So we've got to change.
And the universities better not send them away.
We better leave the fight.
Why am I here?
I'm here because I was a teacher for 10 years in the public schools.
And I couldn't make decisions.
I couldn't make changes.
And I didn't make enough money.
Right?
Okay.
So everybody didn't have the opportunity.
I had to go back and get a doctorate.
We've got to make it work.
That's true.
That's a totally different perception.
And I'm glad to hear it because
Well, I'm strange.
I told you I am.
That's great.
At least it's different.
Well, you've been here, I guess, the least time of anybody that I have talked to, and I think that probably gives you that different perspective that you haven't been here for 30 years or 20 years.
Well, I hope when I have been here for 30 years that I am willing to say, let's do something different.
Let's try it.
Let's be innovative.
If it doesn't work, let's say, well, we made a mistake, but we're not going to.
kill anybody going through here in the process.
There's degrees of quality.
Absolutely.

Okay, so now, with or without your little crystal ball, can you tell me a little bit about, and you have already in passing talked about maybe some of your visions for the future, one being no departments, which would be certainly an innovative program.
What other things do you think the College of Education might be looking at in the 21st century?
Well, the College of Education, you haven't really asked any negative questions here, but I want to tell you something.
Okay.
I looked at this and I thought, how am I going to get in somewhere?
Because I can talk about wonderful stuff out my ears at A&M.
But there are some lovingly critical things I need to say, too.
And I say that adjective because I'm not angry at A&M.
I am delighted to be able to work here.
And sometimes I'm amazed I'm paid to do something I love to do in a place I love to do it.
But A&M has got to...
have some role models for all of the women who are coming through this school.
We have one department head who is a woman in the entire university in sociology.
We used to have a woman in modern languages, but she's no longer there.
And we have had a woman in medicine, Joyce Davis.
I'm not really sure about her, if she's still there or not.
So there may be two.
But for sure, I know there's one, Mary's I. Farrell in sociology.
Now, we have had a woman in the College of Liberal Arts as an assistant dean.
But I'm telling you, if the College of Education does not show that there can be women
in leadership positions, then we're doing a disservice to not only the women, but the men of this university.
And you've already heard me say that I don't like administration, so I'm not trying to make a role for myself here.
I am trying to make a role for talented women here that are generally known as the tremendous teachers at Texas A&M, the wonderful counselors for the students, the great service providers.
but not the decision makers.
And if we don't change that, then we're going to be far behind.
Where do those changes, I mean, let's talk about decision making and the hierarchy and how all of those things can come about, because I'm not familiar.
Being from the outside, looking in, I am not able to perceive the things.
Think about all the development council meetings that you have attended.
how many women do you see getting up to say, let me tell you about my department, let me tell you about...
They win teaching awards because they deserve them, but they are not the people who are in those decision-making roles.
I really thought Dean Cardin would change that, that he has now.
Is he getting any pressure to change that?
Or has he gotten...
The entire university is getting some pressure to look at how women are treated.
This year, we were looked at...
on a case-by-case basis to make sure that we were getting salary increases.
Because we've done a study, I say we, I'm on the committee for the status of women at this university, and I wrote the first report to the president two years ago on what the status of women is here.
And we know that across the board we make 90% of our male colleagues, which is excellent, because nationwide we're making 54 to 60%.
Of what, the males?
Mm-hmm.
And so A&M is really good at paying us 90% of what our male colleagues do.
But I can say that facetiously because, you know, why don't we get the same amount?
So this year, case by case, the deans looked at all women and all minority faculty members, and there was allocated money to make sure that we got appropriate raises so that we were not kept.
Now, again, I work for this, but I am not one of the people who have been mistreated.
I couldn't ever complain about my salary increases, ever.
But looking at case by case, we see that some women can across the university.
Even with a salary increase, what you're saying is that there's still a need to give more roles, for example, like department heads?
Absolutely.
College of Education desperately needs department heads and associate and assistant deans.
If we can't do it,
Nobody else in this whole university can.
Liberal arts can.
They have.
The one department head and the former associate dean.
Do you have some of those reports, maybe copies of some of the reports on the women?
Because that might be something that I could use as a document.
Because I'll be looking not only at the College of Education, but
in relationship to its external environment, the university, and even beyond the university.
So if you have something...
I can get some of that sent to you.
I can get them from the faculty senate office.
Okay.
Any kind of documents that would sort of help me to put this in the right perspective.
You'll have to understand, though, for your report, that the documents will deal on women's faculty in the university, not in the college of ed.
That's fine.
That's fine.
Just, again, because I'm not going to be just looking at the college of ed.
I'll be putting it in the context of
what was happening in the university as well.
Because that obviously has influence on what, you know, what happens in the college.
Absolutely.
Okay, good.
Now, can we talk just for a couple of minutes about some of the highlights maybe?
Hold it just a second.
Let me change the...
